= Conclusion

Armature is a protocol born from a specific diagnosis: Frontier's player-driven civilization cannot emerge without organizational infrastructure. The game provides powerful primitives --- Smart Assemblies that can be composed and programmed to serve any purpose --- but players lack the collective machinery to wield them.

We have built that machinery.

The DAO primitive addresses the four structural barriers to collective action: trust (codified in governance rules and enforced by the type system), ownership (shared custody through treasury and capability vaults), delegation (SubDAO hierarchy with scoped authority and atomic reclaim), and value capture (permissionless deposits, governance-gated withdrawals, and inter-DAO asset flows).

The design is deliberately organic. A DAO is born with a charter, a treasury, and a proposal set. It self-amends through proposals that can modify its own rules. It reproduces through SubDAOs. It emancipates its offspring through spinout. It metabolizes resources through treasury flows. It can die deliberately through migration to a successor. These are not metaphors bolted onto a technical system --- they are structural properties that emerge from the composition of simple primitives.

The security model provides six independent layers of defense --- type system enforcement, governance thresholds, timing controls, emergency circuit breakers, hierarchy controls, and blast radius isolation --- that compose to produce unconditional guarantees: no admin keys, no backdoors, atomic execution, cross-DAO isolation, and permanent auditability.

The current implementation focuses on Board governance, SubDAO hierarchy, and the core proposal system. The roadmap extends to federation (upward composition), direct and weighted governance, proposal composition (atomic multi-step governance), charter parametrization (machine-enforceable policy), project funding, and Smart Assembly integration.

Our thesis remains: the tribe is the atom. Build tribal infrastructure first. Enable tribes to capture value, delegate authority, and scale their operations. From tribal economies, inter-tribe trade will emerge. From trade, a Trinary-wide economic network. From economics, civilization.

We learned the stack from scratch to build something that fits the dreamer --- the player with a vision who needs tools to exercise sovereignty at scale. Our goal is for this framework to grow alongside Frontier's world contracts, to scale and integrate with its systems, and to enable emergent gameplay that no individual product could produce.

Your vision is the unit. Armature gives you the tools to make it real.
